'''''Dives and Pauper''''' is a 15th-century commentary on the [[Ten Commandments]] in dialogue form.<ref>{{Cite journal| issn = 0025-8385| volume = 76| issue = 1| pages = 164–165| last = Connolly| first = Margaret| title = Dives and Pauper, Vol II| journal = Medium Aevum| accessdate = 2017-05-27| date = 2007| url = http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=a9h&AN=27055032&site=ehost-live}}{{subscription|via=Academic Search Complete}}</ref> Written in [[Middle English]], it was most likely authored by a [[Franciscans|Franciscan]] friar. It is structured as a dialogue between a wealthy [[layman]] (Dives) and a spiritual poor man with many similarities to a [[friar]] (Pauper). The work is an example of orthodox [[Catholic]] theology, but it engages many questions relevant to [[Lollardy|Wycliffism]], an English movement condemned as heretical by church authorities.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | title = Dives and Pauper | encyclopedia = The Encyclopedia of Medieval Literature in Britain | publisher = John Wiley & Sons, Ltd. | date = 2017 | access-date = July 31, 2018 | url = https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/9781118396957.wbemlb181 | doi = 10.1002/9781118396957 | ref=harv}}</ref> 

Like [[John Wycliffe]]'s ''De mandatis divinis'', ''Dives and Pauper'' discusses the Commandments in the context of Church law, as well as the "laws of civil society".<ref name=Barnum>{{Cite book| publisher = Oxford University Press for the Early English Text Society| isbn = 978-0-19-722326-0| last = Barnum| first = Priscilla Heath| title = Dives and pauper: (no. 323 in series). Introduction, explanatory notes and glossary| date = 2004}}</ref> Patricia Barnum describes it as a discussion about justice in the context of the "seemingly double standard" of the [[Old Testament]] concept of law (''[[ius]]'') and the [[New Testament]] charity ([[Charity (virtue)|''caritas'']]).<ref name=Barnum/> The question posed is whether God's laws may be harmonized with man's laws. ''Dives and Pauper'' starts the inquiry with the question of what the [[Christian scriptures]] teach about wealth (''temporalia'').<ref name=Barnum/>

